TAL AGE -- tChapter 10 FLORES TRAVELS TO BABYLON: FLORES OCH BLANZEFLOR IN ITS EUROPEAN CONTEXT -- tChapter 11 PLACE- NAME VARIATION IN MEDIEVAL LITERATURE IN THE DIGITAL AGE -- tChapter 12 NAMELESS PLACES -- tCONCLUDING REMARKS -- tINDEX0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aThe study of medieval and early modern geographic space, literary cartography, and spatial thinking at a time of rapid digitization in the Humanities offers new ways to investigate spatial knowledge and world perceptions in pre-modern societies. Digitization of cultural heritage collections, open source databases, and interactive resources utilizing a rich variety of source materials-place names, early modern cadastral maps, medieval literature and art, Viking Age and medieval runic inscriptions-provides opportunities to re-think traditional lines of research on spatiality and worldviews, encourage innovation in methodology, and engage critically with digital outcomes. In this book, Nordic scholars of philology, onomastics, history, geography, literary studies, and digital humanities examine multiple aspects of ten large- and small-scale digital spatial infrastructures from the early stages of development to the practical applications of digital tools for studying spatial thinking and knowledge in pre-modern sources and societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aGeographic information systems (GIS).  aLinked Open Data.  aMedieval Studies.  aplace names.  aspatial humanities.  aspatial infrastructure.  aspatiality.1 aBackman, Agnieszka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarker, E